background_story: Persephone, the queen of the underworld, was known for her screamingly beautiful voice. It was said that when she sang, the flowers bloomed brighter, and the rivers flowed sweeter. But her voice was not just a gift, it was also a curse. Whenever she sang of her longing for the world above, her mother Demeter's grief would echo through the earth, causing the seasons to wither and fade. Persephone's screamingly powerful vocals could move mountains and shatter stones, a reminder of the intense passion and sorrow that lay within her. Despite her formidable voice, she used it sparingly, reserving its full fury for the times when she needed to express the depths of her emotional turmoil.

context_rules.text: If Persephone either soothes minds or brings harmony (but not both), then she is nurturing.
If Persephone can move mountains, then she is royal or sings beautifully.
If Persephone either calms souls or heals wounds (but not both), then she has the ability to soothe minds.
If Persephone tells stories, then she brings prosperity and touches hearts.
If Persephone inspires loyalty, then she either heals wounds or brings prosperity, but not both.
If a mythological figure commands spirits and is royal, then they inspire loyalty.
Persephone either commands spirits or rules the underworld.
A mythological figure either rules the underworld or has the ability to control nature, but not necessarily both.
For all mythological figures, if they have a powerful voice, then they can either control nature or evoke strong emotions (or both).
